Here's how to implement all three in your `EditProductPage`:

**1 & 2. Intercept back navigation and confirm:**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` (hardware/gesture back) and handle the Shell back button via `BackButtonBehavior`:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            ConfirmDiscard();
            return true; // cancel navigation
        }
        return base.OnBackButtonPressed();
    }

    private async void ConfirmDiscard()
    {
        bool discard = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (discard)
        {
            _hasUnsavedChanges = false;
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
        }
    }
}
```

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button in Shell:**

In your XAML, use `BackButtonBehavior` to replace the default arrow:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage"
             Title="Edit Product">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior
            TextOverride="Cancel"
            Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

Then wire up `BackCommand` in your code-behind or view model:

```csharp
// In constructor or property
public ICommand BackCommand { get; }

public EditProductPage()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    BackCommand = new Command(OnBackRequested);
    BindingContext = this;
}

private void OnBackRequested()
{
    if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        ConfirmDiscard();
    else
        Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

**Key points:**
- `OnBackButtonPressed` handles Android hardware/swipe back — return `true` to cancel.
- `BackButtonBehavior.Command` replaces the Shell toolbar back button's default action entirely, so you must navigate manually.
- On iOS, to block the swipe-from-edge gesture too, you may need to disable it when changes exist via a platform-specific handler.
